# Command vs Shell Module

## command Module

Executes commands directly.

Example:

```bash
ansible all -m command -a "uptime"
```

Advantages:

* More secure
* Faster
* Recommended when shell features are unnecessary

---

## shell Module

Executes commands through a shell.

Example:

```bash
ansible all -m shell -a "df -h | grep nvme"
```

Advantages:

* Supports pipes
* Supports redirects
* Supports variables

---

## Comparison Table

| command Module             | shell Module             |                |
| -------------------------- | ------------------------ | -------------- |
| Executes commands directly | Executes through shell   |                |
| More secure                | Less secure              |                |
| Faster                     | Slightly slower          |                |
| No pipes (`                | `)                       | Supports pipes |
| No redirects (`>`, `<`)    | Supports redirects       |                |
| No shell variables         | Supports shell variables |                |
| Recommended by default     | Use only when needed     |                |

---

### Example That Fails with command

```bash
ansible all -m command -a "df -h | grep nvme"
```

Because:

```text
|
```

is a shell feature.

---

### Correct Version

```bash
ansible all -m shell -a "df -h | grep nvme"
```

