ok

TASK [Start nginx service]
ok

TASK [Enable nginx service]
ok
```

Recap:

```text
changed=0
```

---

# Why Idempotency Matters

Without idempotency:

```text
Install package
Install package again
Install package again
Install package again
```

This creates:

* Unnecessary work
* Slow execution
* Unpredictable results

---

With Ansible:

```text
Desired State

Package Present
Service Running
Service Enabled
```

Ansible checks first and changes only when necessary.

---

# Ad-Hoc vs Playbook

| Ad-Hoc Command         | Playbook            |
| ---------------------- | ------------------- |
| One-time task          | Reusable            |
| CLI only               | YAML file           |
| Difficult to scale     | Easy to scale       |
| Not version controlled | Git friendly        |
| Less structured        | Structured          |
| Good for quick tasks   | Good for automation |

---

# Documentation Questions

## What Is a Playbook?

### Answer

A Playbook is a YAML file that defines automation tasks in a structured and repeatable manner. It allows multiple tasks to be executed against managed nodes while maintaining the desired state of the infrastructure.

---

## What Is Idempotency?

### Answer

Idempotency means that running the same playbook multiple times produces the same end state. Ansible changes the system only when necessary and skips tasks that are already compliant with the desired configuration.

Example:

```yaml
dnf:
  name: nginx
  state: present
```

If nginx is already installed, Ansible reports:

```text
ok
